Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear catastrophe to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
However, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with ordinary design flaws that were previously harmless, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
Regarding financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in the derivatives and repo markets, damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although the underlying risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, over-investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and bad luck ensured that the systems were unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a credit freeze on markets for several long weeks.
We now understand the risks and design flaws of Fukushima quite well.
We cannot say the same for the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
At Fukushima, the teams of workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
However, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating derivatives and similar financial structures, over the same active errors.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of the euro's fluctuation but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros by June 1st, and the second promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value compared to another, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as government bonds or mortgage-backed securities, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets at a later time, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or buy back).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a significant portion of the balance sheets of the largest financial institutions, implying that minor financial shocks can affect them greatly.
Certain institutions may then find themselves cut off from repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, as Bear Stearns did.
Individually, transactions on derivatives or repos are hardly blameworthy.
Each separately transfers risk in a legitimate way to those who are better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when they are used excessively by institutions that are vital to the system, they can blow up the financial system, due to their design flaws.
Even today, about 70% of the debt of major American financial institutions is composed of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in the bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in case of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivatives contracts or repos with financially troubled financial institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate, whereas with a bit more time, the company in question might have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos are at the front of the repayment queue in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully limiting their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, anyway.
Of course, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions for derivatives and repo actors put them first in line in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect others to have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
However, the next actor in line is often the US government, as a guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too big to fail, ndt). However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often sticks to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official wants to spoil the party.
The US Congress had an opportunity to solve this flaw in the major overhaul of finance it adopted last summer through the Dodd Frank bill.
But it didn't catch it.
If derivative investors, repo investors, and credit-default swap investors (credit-event derivatives, ndt) did not benefit from favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would insist more often that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by ultra-low capitalizations when it was essentially American government money; they would be less likely to do so if it was their own money at stake.
The public perceives risks of the Fukushima type and risks associated with derivatives differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must face security concerns.
But the derivatives and repo markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets capture public attention and disdain, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with little legislative oversight.
Regarding Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain the risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis using passive cooling systems.
We now consider it possible to design nuclear power plants that can keep fuel rods cool even in the event of a complete loss of electrical power.
However, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damage that prioritizing derivatives and repos could cause in the event of a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require final users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect themselves from unexpected changes in oil prices) and others to engage in high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak market discipline incentives for major financial institutions.
It's as if we are reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully hold investors in derivatives and repos accountable for the risk associated with their decisions when they engage in transactions with systemically vital financial institutions.
Instead, we survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
